            .</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18160403-97-person792">
                  MARY 
                  ANN BIRD
               <interp inst="t18160403-97-person792" type="surname" value="ANN BIRD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160403-97-person792" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160403-97-person792" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner came in, and asked if my father was at home; I told him no; and he asked me if my mother was at home; I told him she was not. Then he went and sit down on a chair; then he got up, and went and looked in the cupboard; then he went and looked on the mantle-piece. This shirt was lying on the table, under the looking-glass, facing the window. He told my little brother not to stare at him, but look out of the window, and see if my mother was coming. Then he said, he would go and have a pint of beer, and come back again. I did not see him take the shirt; but I am sure it was there when he came in; and we missed it after he was gone.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18160403-97-person793">
                  ANN 
                  BIRD
               <interp inst="t18160403-97-person793" type="surname" value="BIRD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160403-97-person793" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160403-97-person793" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was sent for; I am the mother of the last witness. I had this shirt to wash.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18160403-97-person794">
                  WILLIAM 
                  TILLIER
